A ship in harbor is safe, but that is not what ships are built for.

Neither is a 3D printer. Neither is a garage. Neither are you.

### The Idea

The first Industrial Revolution put factories in cities. The 2nd Second Industrial Revolution puts factories in garages — and shops in neighborhoods, and production lines in spare rooms, and manufacturing networks across the country.

Not someday. Now.

### How It Works: Four Levels

**Level 1: The Kit.**
You buy a Canister System for $300. It's a modular injection molding setup with 3D-printed molds that cost $5 instead of $2,000. You start making terrain tiles, game tokens, keychains — whatever you want. Hand-cranked. Kitchen table. Real products.

**Level 2: The Bench.**
You earn Marks by completing manufacturing bounties — testing prototypes, sourcing materials, writing assembly instructions. At 2,000 Marks, the cooperative co-funds a desktop electric injection molder (Babyplast class). You pay a third. The cooperative pays a third. Customer pre-orders pay a third. Now you're filling orders, not just making prototypes.

**Level 3: The Shop.**
An SLS printer arrives — selective laser sintering. Engineering-grade nylon. No molds needed. Now you can make parts for anyone, from any file. Custom orders through the marketplace. Three machines under one roof: Canister System for small batches, Babyplast for volume, SLS for custom. That's a shop.

**Level 4: The Factory.**
Industrial injection press. Steel molds. 50,000+ parts a year. Senior Partners with Guild backing. The cooperative's manufacturing backbone.

### The Rule

DO THE WORK = GET THE STATUS.

No resume. No interview. No loan application. No business plan review committee.

Your Marks are your resume. The threshold is your interview. The revenue share is your contract.

A teenager with a 3D printer can reach Partner faster than an engineer who fills out a form and stops. That's not a bug. That's the design.

### The Medallion

Complete all 13 HexIsle Kickstarter campaigns — back each one within 14 days of the last — and you earn the Ship Medallion. One side: a sailing ship in a gear-shaped wheel. "A ship in harbor is safe, but that is not what ships are built for." The other side: crossed ACME screws behind a QR code. "THE 2ND SECOND INDUSTRIAL REVOLUTION."

The medallion can't be bought. Only earned.

### The Experiment

This is called The Grand Experiment because that's exactly what it is. Nobody has tried this combination before: gamified QA + manufacturing bounties + Marks-based equipment placement + cooperative funding + decentralized production + shared patent portfolio.

The hypothesis: when you let people own what they make, they make more, they make it better, and they make it for each other.

The experiment runs in real time. With real products. Real machines. Real revenue.

If it works, the template is open. Any product. Any community. Any country.

The ship is leaving harbor.

