What if you could injection mold parts at your kitchen table?

Not with a $50,000 machine. Not with hydraulic lines or compressed air. With a set of 3D-printed canisters, a sleeve, and some weights.

### The Problem

Small-scale injection molding has always been caught in an awkward middle. You need more than one part (so hand-making each one is too slow), but you don't need 10,000 (so production tooling is absurdly expensive). The solutions that exist — desktop injection machines for $1,500-$5,000 — still require machined aluminum molds at $200-$2,000 each. And every time you change parts, you rebuild from scratch.

### The Canister Idea

The Canister System replaces all of that with modular, stackable components:

**A/B Canisters:** Two 3D-printed cylinders that fit together with a hex-keyed twist-lock. Your mold cavity sits in the middle. Twist, lock, done. Cost per mold: $5-50 instead of $200-2,000.

**Sleeves:** Standardized tubes that clamp the canisters. Stack them vertically — fill six molds in one shot instead of one at a time.

**The Base:** Where the magic happens. Put your material in the base, put weight on the piston, and gravity pushes it up through every canister in the stack. A one-way valve at the top creates vacuum assist — pulling material upward while gravity pushes from below.

No hydraulics. No compressor. No electrical connections. Gravity and vacuum do the work.

### What Can You Make?

The honest answer: it depends on the material.

Gravity pressure works beautifully for resin, wax, ceramic slip, silicone, and low-melt metals. These materials flow at low pressure — exactly what the Canister System provides. For tabletop gaming terrain (like HexIsle tiles), art casting, jewelry molds, and prototyping, the system works out of the box.

For standard plastics like ABS or polyethylene, you need more pressure than gravity alone provides. That's what the screw press add-on is for — a hand-cranked press that multiplies your force by 245x, reaching the pressures thermoplastics need.

### Why This Matters for the Cooperative

The Canister System turns any member with a 3D printer into a potential production node. Instead of sending your design to a factory and waiting weeks, you print your A/B canister pair, lock it into a sleeve, and start producing parts the same day.

Scale up by stacking more canisters. Scale sideways by running parallel sleeves. Scale the cooperative by sharing mold designs — one member designs the mold, others print and use it.

This is decentralized manufacturing made physical.

