### The Problem

You designed a hex terrain tile. Or a board game token. Or a small enclosure for your sensor project. You printed 10 on your FDM printer. They're fine, but they took 6 hours each and have layer lines.

You need 200. Printing would take 50 days straight.

The obvious answer is injection molding. The problem? A single aluminum mold costs $200 to $2,000. A desktop injection machine costs $800 to $25,000. Setup takes half an hour per run.

### The Canister System

The Canister System replaces all of that with something modular, stackable, and cheap.

**The molds are 3D printed.** An A/B canister pair costs $5-25 to print on an SLA machine. Not $200-$2,000. If you break one, print another.

**Assembly is tool-free.** Two canisters twist-lock together with a 60-degree turn. No bolts, no clamps. The hex-keyed geometry aligns the halves precisely every time. Setup takes 2-5 minutes, not 30.

**It stacks.** Need to fill three molds at once? Stack them. Material flows through a sprue chain from the base upward — all cavities fill simultaneously.

**Two modes.** For resins, wax, silicone, and casting materials: gravity mode. Put weight on top, material flows down. For thermoplastics (the real stuff — PP, PE, ABS): screw press mode on the Small canister. An 8-inch handle with ACME thread generates 5,207 PSI — matching the Morgan Press, the market leader, at a fraction of the price.

### What Can You Make?

Everything the hobbyist desktop molder market already makes:

- Hex terrain tiles and scatter terrain for tabletop games
- Board game tokens, meeples, counters
- Keychains and small merch
- Cosplay accessories and prop details
- IoT sensor housings and small enclosures
- Gear wheels, brackets, mounting clips

These are all small, thick-walled parts with short flow paths — exactly what the S piston was designed for.

### The Numbers

| | Traditional Desktop Molder | Canister System |
|--|---------------------------|-----------------|
| Machine cost | $800-$25,000 | $250-$400 |
| Mold cost per part | $200-$2,000 | $5-$25 |
| Max pressure | 1,200-5,000 PSI | 5,207 PSI |
| Setup time | 15-30 min | 2-5 min |
| Stackable | No | Yes (2-3 for thermoplastics, 6+ for casting) |
| Portable | No | Yes |

At 50 identical parts, the Canister System beats FDM printing on cost per unit. At 200 parts, it's 80% cheaper. And every part is dimensionally identical — no layer lines, no post-processing.

### How to Get Involved

The Canister System is being built through bounties — not by a hired team. CAD designers, 3D print testers, materials sourcers, and QA engineers are all earning Marks for every contribution.

Claim a bounty. Earn Marks. At 500 Marks, you're a Contractor. At 2,000, you're a Partner with revenue share on every kit sold.

We're building 5,000 of these. Every component needs someone to design it, test it, source it, and validate it. That someone could be you.

