Most platforms look the way someone in a design department decided they should look. You get what you get. Maybe you can toggle dark mode. Maybe you can pick a color accent. That's about it.

We think that's backwards.

Liana Banyan is a cooperative. That means the members own it. And if the members own it, shouldn't the members get to decide what it LOOKS like?

### The CSS Zen Garden Idea

Back in 2003, a web designer named Dave Shea created something remarkable. He built one webpage — just one — and invited designers to submit CSS stylesheets for it. Same content. Completely different visual experiences. Some looked like newspapers. Some looked like abstract art. Some looked like video games.

That project proved something important: content and presentation are separate things. You can have the SAME information displayed in radically different ways.

We're bringing that idea to cooperative platform design.

### How It Works

**X-Ray Mode** — Toggle on X-Ray Goggles, and you'll see things normal browsing hides. Tooltips appear. Feedback boxes show up. And on elements where other members have placed design bounties, you'll see a small sign: "You Can Do Better."

**The Overlay** — Click that sign, and a transparent layer appears over the element. Write your replacement text. Upload your alternative image. Submit your version of what that piece of the platform should look like.

**The Vote** — Other members see your submission alongside the original. They vote. If enough people prefer your version, it goes live. The original is preserved in version history — nothing is ever lost.

**Full Page Themes** — Ready for something bigger? Submit an entire CSS stylesheet that transforms a whole page. Other members browse the Theme Gallery, preview your design, and choose to apply it. Your creation becomes part of the platform's visual vocabulary.

### Why This Matters

Design is usually a top-down decision. Someone in charge picks the colors, the fonts, the layout. Everyone else lives with it.

In a cooperative, design becomes a democratic practice. The community decides what beauty means to them. Guilds run banner contests where members compete to define their professional identity. Tribes choose colors that represent their community. Individual members set personal preferences in their Helm.

The platform becomes a living experiment — always evolving, because the community is always creating.

### What You Can Do

- **Browse**: Visit the Theme Gallery to see what others have created
- **Vote**: Support designs you love; the community's taste shapes the platform
- **Create**: Submit element overlays or full page themes
- **Compete**: Enter Guild banner contests to earn Marks and display credit

Design is labor. In this cooperative, design labor is valued, compensated, and democratically chosen.

