-- executive-pay
UPDATE cephas_content_registry
  SET content_markdown = $md_executive_pay$
You already know the story. A CEO makes a bold move — a merger, a pivot, a round of layoffs dressed up as "restructuring." The stock price jumps. The board applauds. The bonus hits the bank account. Eighteen months later, the merger is a disaster, the pivot failed, half the institutional knowledge walked out the door with those laid-off workers, and the stock is back where it started. But the bonus? That's long gone. Spent. Untouchable.

This is not a bug. This is the system working exactly as designed.

And if you've ever wondered why executive compensation feels so disconnected from reality — why the person at the top gets paid like a king even when the castle is on fire — you're asking the right question. You're just asking it to the wrong people.

---

## The Quarterly Thinking Trap

Here's the problem in plain English: most executive pay is tied to short-term results. Hit this quarter's revenue target, get a bonus. Push the stock price up by earnings day, trigger your options. It doesn't matter if you got there by gutting R&D, burning out your workforce, or making promises your company can't keep past December.

The incentive structure literally rewards executives for thinking in 90-day windows. That's not strategy. That's a coin flip with other people's money.

Think about it like this. If I told you I'd pay you a thousand dollars every time your garden looked good on the first of the month, you'd figure out real quick that you could just buy fresh flowers from the store on the 30th and jam them in the dirt. Who cares if nothing has roots? You get paid on the 1st. By the time everything's dead, you've already cashed the check.

That's quarterly-driven executive compensation. Fresh flowers jammed in dirt.

The people who actually built something — the workers who showed up, the middle managers who held things together, the communities that depend on those jobs — they're the ones standing in the garden after the flowers die. The executive is three towns over, negotiating a new contract with a different company, pointing at a resume that says "Increased revenue 15% year-over-year" without mentioning what happened in year three.

---

## Enter the Decision Buffer

So what if we changed the rules?

What if, instead of paying executives the moment a decision *looks* good, we waited to see if it actually *was* good? Not forever. Not punitively. Just... long enough to know.

That's the Decision Buffer.

The concept is simple. When an executive makes a significant decision — a hire, an acquisition, a product launch, a strategic pivot — the compensation tied to that decision goes into a buffer. A holding period. The money is earmarked. It's real. But it doesn't land in the executive's account until the results of that decision have had time to play out.

If the decision works — if it creates sustainable value, if the people affected by it are better off, if the numbers hold up over time — the buffer releases and the executive gets paid. Fully. No penalty for good work that takes time to mature.

But if the decision craters? If that merger turns toxic, if that product launch was built on hype, if those layoffs hollowed out the company's ability to function? The buffer absorbs the loss. The executive doesn't get a windfall for a disaster they created.

This isn't punishment. It's alignment. The executive's paycheck is aligned with the actual outcome of their decisions, not the *appearance* of an outcome on a convenient date.

---

## "But That's Not How It Works Anywhere"

You're right. It's not. And look around at how well that's going.

In the U.S. Army, we had a phrase for leaders who made decisions based on how things would look at the next evaluation rather than what was actually right: "ticket punchers." Get the check in the box, get the promotion, move on before anyone notices the mess you left. Every soldier knows the type. Every soldier has worked for one.

The military eventually figured out — imperfectly, slowly, the way large institutions do — that you need accountability mechanisms with time horizons longer than a single officer's rotation. You need after-action reviews. You need follow-through that outlasts the person who gave the order.

Corporate America hasn't figured this out yet. Or more accurately, it figured it out and decided it didn't care, because the people who benefit from the current system are the same people who'd have to vote to change it.

That's where cooperatives come in.

---

## How This Works at Liana Banyan

At Liana Banyan, we don't have executives in the traditional sense. We have stewards. The difference isn't just vocabulary — it's structural.

A steward's compensation is built on a formula, not a negotiation. We use what we call Cost+20%. The cost of the role — what it genuinely takes to attract and retain someone with the right skills — plus a transparent 20% margin. That's it. No hidden stock options. No golden parachutes. No compensation committee playing poker with shareholder money behind closed doors.

The Decision Buffer layers on top of that. When a steward makes a major allocation decision — directing cooperative resources toward a project, greenlighting a new initiative, approving a significant expenditure — a portion of their variable compensation enters the buffer.

The buffer period varies by decision type. A hiring decision might have a six-month buffer. A major capital allocation might sit for eighteen months. The principle is the same: we wait long enough to see whether the decision actually worked before we pay as though it did.

And here's the part that makes people uncomfortable: the buffer works in both directions. If a steward's decisions consistently create value over time, the buffer releases smoothly and their compensation reflects their good judgment. If decisions consistently underperform, the buffer shrinks their variable pay accordingly. Not as a gotcha — the steward knows the rules going in, same as everyone else. The rules are public. The formula is public. There are no surprises.

This is the opposite of a golden parachute. A golden parachute says: "No matter how badly you perform, you're protected." The Decision Buffer says: "Your compensation is a reflection of your actual impact, measured over time."

---

## The Cost+20% Connection

People sometimes ask why we're so insistent on Cost+20% as our pricing and compensation floor. Here's why: transparency kills corruption.

When you can see exactly how a price is set — cost of goods plus a fixed margin — you can't hide a bonus inside it. You can't inflate your own compensation by "adjusting" the formula. The formula is the formula. Everyone can see it. Everyone can check the math.

Traditional executive comp is the opposite. It's layers of complexity designed to obscure the real number. Base salary, annual bonus, long-term incentive plan, stock options, restricted stock units, deferred compensation, supplemental retirement, perquisites, change-of-control provisions — by the time you've read the proxy statement, your eyes have glazed over and the CEO has made more money in the time it took you to read it than you'll make all year.

That complexity isn't accidental. It's a feature. It makes accountability nearly impossible because you can't hold someone accountable for a number you can't find.

Cost+20% strips all of that away. The Decision Buffer adds the time-delay accountability that ensures even transparent compensation is tied to real outcomes. Together, they create a system where the person in charge has the same incentive as the person on the ground: make good decisions that hold up over time.

---

## What This Means for You

If you work for a traditional company, here's what the Decision Buffer means in practical terms: the system you're in was not designed to protect you.

Your CEO's bonus is not tied to whether you have a job next year. It's not tied to whether your health insurance gets worse. It's not tied to whether the pension fund is solvent or whether the factory stays open. It's tied to a stock price on a specific date, and stock prices can be manipulated in a hundred legal ways that have nothing to do with building anything real.

The Decision Buffer is designed for a different world. One where the person making the big calls has skin in the game on the same timeline as the people affected by those calls. Not "I'll be fine either way" skin in the game — real exposure to the consequences of their own judgment.

In a cooperative, that matters because the members *are* the owners. When a steward makes a bad call, it's the members' resources that get wasted. The Decision Buffer means the steward feels that too. Not just emotionally. Financially.

For ordinary workers — whether you're in a cooperative or not — this should be the standard you demand. Not because executives don't deserve to be well-compensated. They do. Good leadership is rare and valuable. But compensation should be for *actual* good leadership, not for the appearance of it measured on a timeline designed to let someone cash out before the truth arrives.

---

## The Farmer's Principle

There's an old principle in cooperative economics that goes back to the Rochdale Pioneers in 1844: democratic member control. One member, one vote. The people affected by decisions should have a say in those decisions.

The Decision Buffer is the compensation equivalent of that principle. It says: the person making decisions should be affected by those decisions on the same timeline as everyone else. Not faster. Not with an escape hatch. On the same timeline.

A farmer doesn't get to declare the harvest successful in June. She has to wait until fall. She has to live with the weather, the pests, the soil conditions — all the variables that determine whether the work actually paid off. If she plants the wrong crop, she doesn't get to collect a bonus and move to a different farm before the frost hits.

That's all the Decision Buffer is. The executive version of having to wait for the harvest.

We built Liana Banyan on a simple conviction: the structures that determine who gets what should be transparent, formula-driven, and tied to outcomes that benefit everyone — not just the person at the top of the org chart. The Decision Buffer is how we make that conviction operational at the leadership level.

Your boss's bonus should have a time delay. Not because we don't trust leadership. Because we trust the process more than we trust any individual, and a process that pays for results before they exist isn't a process at all.

It's a magic trick. And you're not the magician.

---

## Ready to Join?

**[Walk the Red Carpet](https://lianabanyan.com/red-carpet)** — Your cooperative membership starts here. $5/year.

---

